      "widgets_values": [
        "COMPOSABLE GEOMETRY DERIVATION — Nuke-style, wired instead of a preset\n\nThe alternative to AtlasDeriveProjectionGeometry's scene_type presets: instead\nof one node with a combo that silently locks/hides other widgets, each\nderivation strategy is its own single-purpose node with only the parameters\nthat actually apply to it. Compose a shot by wiring nodes together, like a\nNuke script, and use ④ AtlasMergeGeometry (a real Merge node, not implicit\nchaining) to combine branches.\n\n1. ③ AtlasDepthMap estimates depth ONCE from the source photo — every\n   derivation node downstream shares this SAME depth estimate. This matters\n   for correctness, not just speed: if two branches each ran their own depth\n   pass, their independently-fitted ground scales could disagree slightly,\n   and the merged geometry wouldn't line up.\n\n2. This example forks into two branches from the same solve + depth:\n     ① Foreground (node ④, AtlasDeriveWalls) — vertical walls + foreground\n        boxes/cylinders (buildings). max_objects is bumped to 6 here since\n        this branch is meant to catch buildings.\n     ② Background (node ⑤, AtlasDeriveReliefMesh) — continuous relief mesh\n        for terrain/treeline, at 'medium' quality.\n   Swap either for AtlasDeriveTowersSpires / AtlasDeriveRoofsFacades /\n   AtlasDeriveInteriorRoom depending on the shot — every one of these nodes\n   takes the same solve + depth inputs.\n\n3. IMPORTANT: derive nodes never chain on their own — each one strips any\n   prior derived geometry from the solve before adding its own (so re-running\n   one never silently piles up stale geometry). That means you CANNOT wire\n   node ④'s output directly into node ⑤'s solve input and expect both\n   branches to survive — node ⑤ would erase node ④'s walls. This is exactly\n   why node ⑥ (AtlasMergeGeometry) exists: it's the one explicit place two\n   branches' geometry actually combines. Chain multiple AtlasMergeGeometry\n   nodes for 3+-way combination (Merge(fg,bg) -> Merge(that, a third branch)).\n\n4. AtlasMergeGeometry also dedupes the always-emitted 'projection_backdrop'\n   plane (every derivation strategy emits exactly one) so you don't get two\n   overlapping backdrop planes — it keeps solve_a's.\n\n5. Node ⑥'s merged solve feeds the viewport exactly like any other solve —\n   no viewport-side changes needed. Hit 📽 Project (in the viewport, or in an\n   AtlasViewportControls node if you've split it out) to see both branches'\n   geometry textured from the recovered camera at once.\n\nNote: solve_a (wired to AtlasMergeGeometry's first input) provides the\nmerged solve's camera/intrinsics — both branches here come from the same\nupstream AtlasLearnedSolveFromImage, so they already share a camera."
      ]
    }
